      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(inworld): bound TTS audio and error response body reads to prevent OOM",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nThe Inworld streaming TTS endpoint read its response with an **unbounded** `await response.text()` (`extensions/inworld/tts.ts:97`) before splitting the newline-delimited JSON and concatenating the base64 audio chunks. The endpoint returns a server-sent stream, so a controlled/hijacked endpoint (malicious proxy, compromised base URL) can stream an arbitrarily large body that is fully buffered into memory — an unbounded-flood → OOM vector. The non-OK error body (`extensions/inworld/tts.ts:93`, and the analogous `listInworldVoices` path) was likewise read in full.\n\nThis wraps the audio read in the canonical `readResponseWithLimit` helper (the same `@openclaw/media-core` helper PR #95108 introduced to bound the Anthropic Messages error read), and reads error bodies via `readResponseTextSnippet`. Audio bodies are legitimately large, so the cap is **32 MiB** = `2 × MAX_AUDIO_BYTES` (the shared 16 MiB audio limit), leaving headroom for base64 inflation (~4/3) plus the NDJSON envelope. The stream is cancelled at the cap or on stall instead of buffering unbounded, and normal payloads still decode.\n\n## Changes\n\n- `extensions/inworld/tts.ts`\n  - Import `readResponseWithLimit` + `readResponseTextSnippet` from `openclaw/plugin-sdk/response-limit-runtime` and `MAX_AUDIO_BYTES` from `openclaw/plugin-sdk/media-runtime` (existing plugin entries; no new abstraction).\n  - Add `INWORLD_TTS_BODY_MAX_BYTES = MAX_AUDIO_BYTES * 2` (32 MiB) with a 30s idle timeout; replace the line-97 `await response.text()` with the bounded reader (`onOverflow` / `onIdleTimeout` throw bounded errors), then `.toString(\"utf8\")` and split exactly as before.\n  - Add a small `readInworldErrorBodySnippet(response)` wrapper (8 KiB / 400 char cap, 10s idle) and use it for both the `inworldTTS` and `listInworldVoices` non-OK error bodies.\n- `src/plugin-sdk/response-limit-runtime.ts`\n  - Re-export `readResponseTextSnippet` alongside `readResponseWithLimit` so extensions can use the #95108 snippet helper through the plugin-sdk entry.\n- `extensions/inworld/tts.test.ts`\n  - Regression tests: oversized audio stream → cap error + stream cancelled after a bounded number of pulls; oversized HTTP error body → truncated bounded snippet (never the full body). Existing 16 tests unchanged.\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n- **What was run**: a standalone `tsx proof.mts` driving the **real** `inworldTTS` (the SSRF runtime swapped for a controllable stub via a Node `resolve` hook so the real body-read path runs against synthetic streams without network/loopback SSRF opt-in), plus the new `vitest` regression tests and `oxlint` / `tsgo` on the changed files. Worktree off `upstream/main` with the repo `node_modules` symlinked.\n- **Before (unbounded)**: draining the same flood stream the way `await response.text()` does internally read **67108864 bytes (64 MiB)** and never stopped (the demo guard cut it off; a real infinite stream → OOM). The old code had no cap.\n- **After (bounded, this PR)**: the same flood through the real `inworldTTS` pulled only **6 × 8 MiB chunks**, hit the 32 MiB cap, **cancelled the stream** (the stream's `cancel()` callback fired), and threw `Inworld TTS audio stream too large: 41943040 bytes (limit: 33554432 bytes)`.\n- **Error body**: a 64 KiB HTTP 500 body produced a **430-char** message (`Inworld TTS API error (500): EEE…`), never inlining the full 64 KiB body.\n- **Negative control**: a normal NDJSON payload (`{result:{audioContent:<base64>}}`) still decodes fully — the returned `Buffer` equals `real-audio-bytes`, no false positive (legitimate large-but-bounded responses are not broken).\n- **Readback**: the proof reads the actual thrown `Error.message`, the stream's `cancel`-callback invocation, the enqueued-chunk count, and the resolved/decoded `Buffer` across the real read path (not a mock of the helper).\n- **Tests / lint / types**: `vitest extensions/inworld/tts.test.ts` → **19 passed** (3 new); `oxlint` on the 3 changed files → exit 0; `tsgo -p tsconfig.extensions.json` and `tsgo -p tsconfig.core.json` → exit 0.\n- **Result**: all proof assertions passed (`=== proof summary: 5 passed, 0 failed ===`).\n\n**Label**: security\n\n## Symmetry with #95108\n\n#95108 bounded the analogous Anthropic Messages **error-response** read with `readResponseWithLimit` / `readResponseTextSnippet`. This PR is the symmetric fix for the Inworld TTS **main audio stream** (plus its error bodies), reusing the same `@openclaw/media-core` helper via the `response-limit-runtime` plugin entry (which this PR extends to also re-export `readResponseTextSnippet`) rather than introducing a new abstraction.\n\n---\n\nAI-assisted: implemented and verified with AI assistance; all proof commands were run for real against the actual code path.\n",
